    'month' => '12',
    'topic' => ' GURPS:Trav ships',
    'body' => '>Date: Wed, 29 Dec 1999 09:20:46 -0400
>From: Les_Howie@keane.com
>Subject: GURPS:Trav ships
>
>Would some kind soul please fill me in on how ship design and combat work in
>GURPS:Traveller.

Could you be more specific? Are you sitting confused with a copy of GT in
your lap, or are you curious as to what the differences from previous
versions may be (say, before you buy it)?

Assuming the latter, GT uses simplified versions of the rules for vehicle
design and combat from GURPS Vehicles, optimized for starships and space
combat. 

The design system uses packages of components in multiples of 1 dton (=500
cubic feet, using American units for compatibility with GURPS). These
packages are supposed to be modular, in that they can be swapped around
during the design process without recursive calculations. (The resulting
vessel is *not* modular, however.)

One significant drawback of the modular approach was that a "slice" of
power plant was included in each module to meet its power requirements.
This eliminates recursive power calculations, but the resulting designs are
over-powered (they can run *all* systems simultaneously, whether needed or
not), the size of the power plant is obscured (bad when you\'re trying to
create deck plans), and minor changes in the configuration (e.g., swapping
turret lasers for missile racks) actually cause the size of the power plant
to change as well. The modular design system in GURPS Space, 3d Edition, is
a refinement of that in GT. With separate power plants and power
requirements, it is much more elegant.

The combat system is hex-based, with 10,000-mile hexes and 20-minute turns,
and uses a vector movement system (very similar to TNE\'s Battle Rider
wargame). Multiple shots over the length of a turn are abstracted into a
single roll to hit; higher rates of fire result in bonuses to the to-hit
roll. Emphasis is on character skills -- good pilots, sensor operators, and
gunners are important to successful actions. Missiles are laser command
guided, primarily because sensors small enough to mount on them are
inadequate at the ranges involved in space combat.

The ship design and space combat rules for GT were intended to replicate
the "look and feel" of Classic Traveller under GURPS rules (which, being
generic, require many specific choices to make them applicable to a given
setting). All in all, they succeed more often than not.
