    'from' => 'Kiri Aradia Morgan tiamat@tsoft.com',
    'body' => 'On Wed, 29 Dec 1999, Robert Prior wrote:

> >And it\'s the moral/ethical
> >dilemmas that are why no one has tried it in vitro. You\'d have to deal
> >with questions such as "is this to be treated like a fertilized human
> >egg? Or as just another animal experiment?"
> 
> How do they handle the ethics when they\'re experimenting with fertility
> treatments?
> 
They tend to let the courts decide, as with recent cases involving the
disposition of unused embryos (IVF requires the creation of more
embryos than are usually implanted) and whether or not a woman should be
allowed to impregnate herself with her dead husband\'s banked sperm.  

> I suspect that implantation and pregnancy would be bigger hurdles than
> fertilization. There\'s a lot of chemical interaction between fetus and
> mother, which means a lot of places for things to go wrong.
> 
Yup.  This is the problem with the interfertility between the minor human
races in my universe.  Conception is no big deal but there are problems
during the term of the pregnancy if a roll goes off.  You see, while the
basic A/B/AB/O blood types are *fairly* well distributed among human
racial groups there are a lot of antibodies, etc, that are not --
some are rare enough to be associated not just with certain ethnic
groups but with certain localities and groups of families.

That\'s why typing blood for blood transfusions is so important and why
it\'s not enough to just know the type, because people have antibodies in
their blood that can cause hemolytic transfusion reactions that can make
you very sick and even kill you dead.  Bone marrow matches are even
trickier which is why persons of Asian descent and/or mixed race are
always being recruited.

The Rh factor is a known problem in pregnancies-- if the baby has it and
the mother does not, big trouble in second or third pregnancies-- although
there\'s a treatment that fixes that one!  Imagine the difference in Vilani
and Solomani blood types given the isolation of the two groups from one
another and the different environments they have had to adapt to.  I
wouldn\'t want a transfusion from a Vilani unless I knew I was GOING TO DIE
without it!  The likelihood of an incompatible antibody on one side or the
other would be fairly high-- probably not worth it unless your Hgb was 8
or less. 

I would think that pregnancies across these lines would carry a
significantly greater risk than normal.   Probably one that Imperial
physicians know how to deal with efficiently by 1116-- maybe as easy to
handle as giving a shot of Rhogam after childbirth-- but still not
something to laugh at.  As for carrying a human/chimp hybrid to term-- I
think that would be very difficult.

Kiri Aradia Morgan
Administrative Assistant, UCSF Dept. of Biochemistry
former secretary to the UCSF/Mt. Zion Blood Utilization and Transfusion
Committee

