    'index' => 'ej290',
    'body' => 'My qualifications: I work in the computer game industry, and have dealt 
with a number of bitmap formats over the last 10 years.

William F. Hostman wrote:
> .JPG was, at least in early implementations, primarily for scanned files.
> Almost every scanning program I\'ve encountered either uses TIFF (.TIF) or
> uncompressed .JPG.

.JPG wasn\'t specifically conceived for scans; it was designed for any
purpose where 24-bit color was desired, but lossy compression was 
needed. 

> JPEG uses a full width system. I can, if my display supports it, use any
> 256 colors of the 32 bit pallate in a .GIF; for non-scanned/photographed
> images, especially those created by direct pixelpopping, 256 colors will be
> more than sufficient. 256 is one byte; the 32 bit wide is 3 bytes.

You\'re mistaken on several points. GIF palettes (and most 8-bit/256 
color palettes you\'ll encounter) select from a 24-bit gamut (2^24 = 
16 million colors), not a "32-bit palette". "Direct pixelpopping" is 
out of fashion, and today\'s computer game artists would laugh at you
if you said "256 colors will be more than sufficient". 256 colors 
is one byte; 32 bits is technically four bytes, not three, but the 
lossy compression used by JPEG means the actual space used per 
pixel can vary widely.

> Additionally, most people I\'ve met don\'t go the whole 32bit route on their
> screens; they use 24 bit graphics at best, simply due to the limits of
> their Video ram.

Incorrect. There is no difference between 32 and 24 bit displays 
(unless you want to talk about destination alpha buffers); the 
use of one or the other generally depends on whether the video
hardware in question prefers pixels to be aligned on 32-bit 
boundaries for hardware simplification (32 bits/pixel = 4 bytes = 
nice round binary numbers; 24 bits/pixel = 3 bytes = more logic 
needed to address a pixel). 

> the whole thread was based around sharing images ON THE WEB. If I\'m going
> to put images on the Web, it becomes VITAL to know the stregths and
> weaknesses of the various formats. And, for doing things like deckplans,
> .gifs are generally going to maintain the crisp lines better.

To get back to the GIF-versus-PNG thing, let my throw in my Cr0.02.

Please, please, please use PNG for all your lossless web graphics. 
The reasons? The free Unixoid operating systems (Linux, *BSD) support 
it, it\'s supported by the major browsers in use today: Opera, IE 4.x, 
and Netscape 4.x, it\'s *more* flexible than GIF in that it supports 
lossless compression of 24-bit images, and isn\'t going to have its 
licensing terms changed every time Unisys sneezes.

- -Russell Bornschlegel
