    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'At 01:46 am 12/29/99 -0000, you wrote:
>>    Wasn\'t the official deckplan 1.5m x 1.5m? I think they listed a
Dton as
>>6.75
>
>
>Actually, now I think about it I\'m sure it varied between rulesets.
The TNE
>disp-ton was 14m3, the volume of 1 metric tonne of liquid hydrogen,
but I
>think the value used in CT and TNE was different. (Although I don\'t
think it
>was as small as 6.75m3 - I could be wrong.)

	CT defined 1 disp ton to be the volume displaced by one metric ton
mass of liquid hydrogen, which is 14m^3 (+/-). MT kept the definition
but changed the volume to 13.5m^3 to make life easier for
anal-retentive deckplan artists who wanted an exact number of squares
per Dt (1.5m squares, 3m deck=6.75m^3=0.5 Dt[MT]). TNE went back to
14m^3, changed the squares to 2m and 3.5m decks (7m^3=0.5Dt[TNE]),
and reminded everybody of the "slop" rule in drawing deckplans ...
*I* always wanted a decent 3D CAD/modelling tool so I didn\'t have to
have square ships but could still get "accurate" ship layouts.

