    'topic' => 're:  Santanocheev, the man...',
    'body' => '>Dan Roseberry <rosebee@troi.csw.net>

>What language is Santanocheev derived from?

I think it\'s a Solomani name, a corruption and blend
of Spanish "Santa" or "Santana" with a Slavic "chev"
or "cheff".  

>Who were Santanocheev\'s "political and social
>connections"? the persons who had promoted him to
>Sector Admiral 

I\'ve assumed that he was well connected to the court
of the Matriarch of Mora.  Mora is the sector capital,
so the Matriarch (who also holds the Imperial title
Duchess of Mora) wields a lot of power in the sector.

>Were they pushing Santanocheev\'s promotions in an 
>attempt to replace Norris with someone more to their 
>liking?

No.  Norris\'s only position at the beginning of the
war was Duke of Regina; no one was trying to put
Santanocheev into that spot.  

Norris wasn\'t a serving naval officer at the beginning
of the war.  (During the war, Norris took over naval
operations in the sector pursuant to the Imperial
Warrant.)

>Finally, after Santanocheev was sacked, he demanded a

>board of inquiry into why he had been relieved (TNS 
>bulletin 010-1110)  He continued to demand an inquiry

>after he had retired (TNS bulletin 146-1110). What 
>were the results of the inquiry, if any? What did he 
>do after he retired?

Canon doesn\'t say.  

The board of inquiry would probably find that ONI was
established beyond Santanocheev\'s authority and
hampered the war effort, so Santanocheev would receive
some Imperial censure, possibly including a downgrade
in noble rank (I\'ve forgotten his noble status, if
any; is there an official UPP for Santanocheev?).  

Santanocheev would not be found guilty (nor even
charged with) any more serious offense like treason. 
He was just power-mongering, and may be able to
justify his actions based on review of intelligence
reports that were being provided to him.  

Santanocheev retired.  He might have been invited to
resign from the Navy, or he might simply have been
assigned to some job where he couldn\'t cause any harm
for the rest of his career, and decided that he\'d had
enough.  He might have just felt humiliated at his
treatment at Norris\'s hands after Norris got the
warrant.  He might have just gotten old and decided
that he didn\'t want to run any more wars, but would
rather tend his garden and enjoy his wife and
grandchildren.

Post-war Santanocheev might be an interesting factor
in a game.  The obvious possibilities are:

1) Santanocheev seeks revenge on Norris for Norris\'
exposing him as the incompetent he truly is.  The PCs
might be hired by Santanocheev to discredit Norris in
some way, or by Norris to protect him from
Santanocheev.

2) "When you get tired of checking your porridge for
broken glass, you are tired of being a sector duke." 
Norris, paranoid but not unreasonably so, plans to
whack Santanocheev.  The PCs are hired by one side or
the other.

3) Santanocheev is trying to clear his name (probably
during the board of inquiry), and hires the PCs to get
evidence, possibly in the form of testimony from
Zhodani operatives or naval personnel, or Zhodani
naval or governmental records.  This operation could
be overt, covert, or both.  The overt operation is to
hire a Zhodani lawyer to help get through the various
bureaucracies and get the Zhodani to care enough about
the problem.  The covert operation is obvious.  Both
can happen at once.  

- --Glenn
