    'topic' => ' Re Image Formats',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> The benefits that GIF"s have over JPGs for web use are support for
> "see-thru" colours and animation, and they use "lossless" compression. But
> of course they are only "lossless" if the original picture is one of the
> limited number of supported formats. If it isn\'t, and most non-digital
> photographs aren\'t, then saving a picture as a GIF will cause you to lose
> definition.

Excuse me? If the original has more than 256 colors, then, yes GIF will
lose detail. But GIF is *not* limited (at least in any serious mannar)
as to image *size*. I have a couple of GIF files that were produced by
converting output from some CAD-like application. They are several
*thousand* pixels on a side. 

GIF will "waste" a bit of space if the number of colors isn\'t a
multiple of 2. But that\'s pretty trivial. It can handle anything from
mono to 256 colors.

PNG goes all the way to 32-bit color, so it doesn\'t even have *that*
limitation. 

>> They are generally fairly low in overhead.
>
> JPEG really has no more overhead than GIF, except that a heavily compressed
> one might take a little longer to save and display. OTOH, a non-compresed
> one should display faster, as it is basically a straight bitmap.

JPEGs seem to use a *lot* more CPU than GIFs. I base this on having
dealt with both on "underpowered" systems. 

- -- 
