> >One significant drawback of the modular approach was that a "slice" of
> >power plant was included in each module to meet its power requirements.
> >This eliminates recursive power calculations, but the resulting designs
are
> >over-powered (they can run *all* systems simultaneously, whether needed
or
> >not), the size of the power plant is obscured (bad when you\'re trying to
> >create deck plans), and minor changes in the configuration (e.g.,
swapping
> >turret lasers for missile racks) actually cause the size of the power
plant
> >to change as well. The modular design system in GURPS Space, 3d Edition,
is
> >a refinement of that in GT. With separate power plants and power
> >requirements, it is much more elegant.
> >
> From GURPS Traveller Second Edition:
>
> As for being able to run **all** systems simultaneously, Star Trek
> notwithstanding, as an old Navy man I can tell you no seaman would dream
of
> serving on a ship that didn\'t have excess power generation capability. I
can
> only assume that spacers would feel the same. Remember fusion power is
> cheap. Fuel for jump is expensive (at least in terms of tankage and such).
> But power itself is cheap. (A milieu 0 campaign might be different, but in
> the Twelfth Century Imperial an undamaged ship should never want for
power.)
>
>
Terry,

For a military ship I whole heartedly agree with you. However, I can see the
problem in this system for ship UPGRADES. Say a PC party has the money to
install a couple of lasers on their ship, why is it CERTAIN that they will
have the credits, room, appropriate peripheral equipment, etc. to upgrade
their Power Plant (not to mention remebering the fact that it\'s too small to
accomodate everything at once!).

Heck I played this on my old party, CT of course. They had the ship, made
enough to add some fire power and figured they could take on the Universe!
First time a pirate came along they decided to "burn \'em from the skies!".
Loaded the appropriate gunnery software, manned the turrets got ready to
fire! Then I asked them what systems they were going to shut down! I also
suggested that the drives were the single system that could be shut down
that would give them all of the power they needed. Of course there was a
time penalty to restart the drives, made longer for each round they fired.

I used some of the old FASA Star Trek rules for engineering and had them
sweating for a while, until their engineer managed to shut down enough
secondary system (including life support) and pulled a bit more than the
rated power out of the PP to let them get a couple of shots off AND keep the
drives running! As it worked out they had AMAZINGLY good rolls (wink, wink)
and crippled the raider. It was a long time before they got over the
humbling experience, they also save they cash to increase the PP, then they
found out how much of their cargo hold they would lose...

It was like that with every upgrade, once they caught one, always a
trade-off. With the G:T rules the trade-off is in space alone... if you
include the PP as a percentage of the module. I prefer the modified modules
(from somewhere on the \'Net) with out the PP percentage, and a seperate
number of PP modules sized as needed.

Mike
