A/UX was Apple\'s UNIX implementation (or rather, impersonation), which was a
native UNIX which could also call the stuff in the Apple ROMs. It got dropped
in the early 90\'s in favour of AIX, which was in turn dropped shortly before
Jobs came back on board.

There was a product called (I think) Executor which ran on, among other things,
Linux. It required you to have an Apple ROM on hand though. I\'ve no idea what
became of it.

There was a software only emulator for Sun, HP and AIX called Macintosh
Application Services (MAS), around the time AIX 3.2 came out. But Apple started
playing silly games with the licensing (I think it was really a tease while
they were talking to various parties about being bought) that it was never
released, on AIX at least.

But there was an advert at the time showing an RS/6000 running Hypercard under
MAS alongside a bunch of Smartsuite stuff under WABI (emulating Win3.1), and
some GL and some other stuff. I set up the systems for the photoshoot and I can
tell you that it did actually work.

M
