in
>> the Twelfth Century Imperial an undamaged ship should never want for
power.)
>>
>>
>Terry,
>
>For a military ship I whole heartedly agree with you. However, I can see
the
>problem in this system for ship UPGRADES. Say a PC party has the money to
>install a couple of lasers on their ship, why is it CERTAIN that they will
>have the credits, room, appropriate peripheral equipment, etc. to upgrade
>their Power Plant (not to mention remebering the fact that it\'s too small
to
>accomodate everything at once!).
>
>Heck I played this on my old party, CT of course. They had the ship, made
>enough to add some fire power and figured they could take on the Universe!
>First time a pirate came along they decided to "burn \'em from the skies!".
>Loaded the appropriate gunnery software, manned the turrets got ready to
>fire! Then I asked them what systems they were going to shut down! I also
>suggested that the drives were the single system that could be shut down
>that would give them all of the power they needed. Of course there was a
>time penalty to restart the drives, made longer for each round they fired.
>
>
>It was like that with every upgrade, once they caught one, always a
>trade-off. With the G:T rules the trade-off is in space alone... if you
>include the PP as a percentage of the module. I prefer the modified modules
>(from somewhere on the \'Net) with out the PP percentage, and a seperate
>number of PP modules sized as needed.
>
>Mike
>
Not a bad way to make the players sweat.
My preference would be to go with a more reality based scenario. For example
if the upgrade was done at a reputable shipyard then a Naval Architect would
have had to do the designs (Cha-Ching). He would most certainly notify the
customer that the ship would be under powered, and require a bigger power
plant (Cha-Ching), resulting in loss of cargo space. Should the players
decide to go ahead with the design without the upgrade then there\'s no way
that the TAS and shipyard inspectors would pass the ships as safe for use in
Imperial space. Of course they might be amiable to convincing (Cha-Ching).
And of course, unauthorized and illegal modifications to a vessel still
under mortgage could cause the bank to determine that the loan was in
default and cause a skip agent or two to visit to reclaim the vessel. Then
play out the attack. The fact that they\'d been warned won\'t make them feel
any better, especially if the Architect is sufficiently vague about what
"underpowered" means.


Terry C
