    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>> "If your scenario calls for large quantities of children, a deck
>>> dedicated to play may be necessary. Playrooms should be designed
>>> with an eye toward teaching survival skills to groups of different
>>> ages, and they must be fun."

>>One world\'s "survival skills" is quick way to get *very* dead on
>>another world.
>
> Certainly true. However the concept isn\'t bad. Children on shipboard will
> definitely need to know survival skills not necessary for their planet bond
> brethren.  What do they do on a loss of gravity? A loss of power? And what
> do they do in the case of a vacuum leak? They better know. A child as young
> as five better know how to climb into a Rescue Ball.

I expect that "cradles" and even "pappoose carriers" will double as
rescue balls. In fact, they\'ll probably be *sturdier* than rescue
balls. Hard shelled with a "cover that snaps down against a gasket at
the first pressure drop. A 15 minute oxy tank for an adult is about the
size of a baby. And isn\'t all *that* heavy. It should last a real baby
an hour or more (much more if the unit incorporates elementary
"re-breather" filtration).

Kids large enough to run around with minimal supervision (say bright
3-year olds on up) will probably be trained to *always* have with them
a small pack/satchel that contains a children\'s rescue ball. Smaller,
and again probably somewhat tougher (partly to withstand handling by
kids!).

> A ten year old should
> know how to use a vac suit (if they regularly live on a ship or on a world
> without a breathable atmosphere.)  They should know how to operate an
> airlock and when it\'s safe to go outside on a strange planet and when the
> indicating lights on the airlock say it\'s not safe. They should know how to
> operate the ship\'s communication system and the computer (which should have
> guards to prevent them from doing anything that will endanger the ship.)
> They should know where and the ship they aren\'t allowed to go (most likely
> the engineering sections and possibly the bridge/control room.)

Actually, going by *farm* life, kids as young as 8 will be operating
the simpler equipment. They may have "chores" that involve doing the
simpler tasks in the control room or enegineering. And they\'ll know
*quite* well what they are and aren\'t allowed to touch. 

They\'ll be *training* on stuff they aren\'t allowed to do on their own
yet. Many\'s the ship where in an accident, one of the kids used this
training to take care of something when there wasn\'t *time* (or
opportunity) for an adult to deal with it in time. 

A kid may not be certified to run the powerplant yet, but the *first*
thing he was taught was how to recognize the warning signals, and the
right way to do a shutdown for various problems. 

So if there are a couple of "junior cadets" in engineering, cleaning
and checking "safe" secondary systems, and something goes wrong and
takes out the engineer on duty, you can bet that one of them is
notifying control and tending to the injured man while the other is
trying to shut down whatever system has gone nuts. 

> Really young children will probably require constant attention (which
> they need anyway) and be limited to a few rooms that have been "child
> safed".

Which, on shipboard, includes special filters on the air returns.
*Especially* if zero g is present any amount of the time. The last
thing you want to get into the air system are pieces of toys, "spit-up"
and worse. :-)

> Older children will probably have chores necessary to ship operation
> (very much like farm children), especially on a working trader.

Yep. See above. 

Oh yeah, a duty that kids almost *always* draw... "dusting" the air
ducts. The ducts aren\'t all *that* long or complex on any reasonable
sized ship. But they *are* small enough that you have a choice between
an expensive robot, giving an adult galloping claustrophobia, and using
the kids. 

In port, kids barely old enough to read well may be helping the cargo
master check containers of cargo in and out. Sure, the automatics log
the stuff, but a manual backup (the cargo master and the "supercargo"
:-) never hurts. 

