>> > (several exchanges later, Sid\'s Vargr kicks the marine to death, while
>
> Hmmmm... correct me if I am wrong here, but I have always thought
> Vargr physiology makes their kicks pretty ineffective, right? I seem
> to remember the rule of thumb... "Vargr can\'t kick." <shrug>.

Forwards? I tend to agree. But *backwards* is a whole different story.
Being digigrade[1], rather than plantigrade[2], Vargr are likely to be
able to kick well *behind* themselves, and also do *nasty* "belly
rakes" to someone they\'ve grappled with.

[1] walking with only the toes and "toe pad" on the ground, and what
    would be the rest of the foot on a human bein a long set of bones
    leading up to a hock(?) which is the joint that\'s the heel & ankle
    on humans.

[2] Walking with those bones on the ground, and the hock(?) being an
    ankle.

Note. If you ever try to "walk digigrade" keep in mind that it is *not*
done like a human on tip-toe. Instead, both the ankle *and* the knee
are kept bent. This keeps the center of gravity over the ground contact
points, but results in a *very* different gait. Sort of a "glide". Even
without make-up, you look quite non-human.

It\'s a strain for humans to walk this way for long. I can\'t even do it
since I gained some weight. My ankles aren\'t up to it, and my knees
aren\'t real happy either.

Anyway, if you try, you\'ll probably *know* when you get it right
because all of a sudden it\'s *easier* to move than in any other posture
except our "normal" one.

