    'from' => 'eris@pcola.gulf.net',
    'body' => 'On 12/30/99 at 12:26 PM,  "Terry Carlino" <carlino@home.com> said:

>> As for being able to run **all** systems simultaneously, Star
>> Trek notwithstanding, as an old Navy man I can tell you no seaman
>> would dream of serving on a ship that didn\'t have excess power
>> generation capability.

There\'s underpowered and then there\'s *really* underpowered.  <g> I
rate power requirements at three levels when I design ships.  First,
there\'s the power requirement with *every* system at full power,
ships sometimes carry a reactor this powerful.  Second, is the power
requirement will all systems that would be running similtaniously
(don\'t need power maneuver in jump space or jump drive/grid in
normal space, CG/AG doesn\'t have to run at full power at all times,
etc.), every ship should *exceed* this number.  Third, is minimum
power to keep the ship\'s life support and Jump Grid running for when
emergencies strike, many ships carry a secondary energy source rated
at, at least, this level.

When damage or malfunction reduces the power from the engines things
can get dicey for the PC\'s.  I, too, have had situations where the
PC\'s had to juggle power among various systems. <g>

Eris
