    'body' => 'A few more waysd to keep your players on their toes:

Given the history of the Imperium, there are going to be laws that are
multiple *thousands* of years old, that have never been explicitly
repealed, but aren\'t enforced anymore either. If you are *careful* you
can take advantage of this. But it could backfire.

A couple of real world examples:

Back in Victorian times, a man who was likely going to lose a civil
suit noted that trial by combat was technically still legal. So he sent
proper notification to the court and the other party in the suit. 

He showed up, in armor, at the appointed place and time and
(apparently) so did an officer of the court. Since the other party had
declined the challenge, he won the case!

Parliment eliminated this "loophole" next session. 

More recently (in the last 5-10 years) a student at Oxford noted that
the rules of the College required the College to provide "ale and
cakes" for the "young gentlemen" sitting examinations. So, next exam
time, he requested the "ale and cakes" pointing to the regulation.
After a bit of discussing, it was decided that some burgers and a pint
(or some such) were an acceptable modern equivalent. And they presented
them to him, and he happily muched and sipped his way thru his exams. 

Alas, after completing them, he was presented with notice that he was
being fines 25 pounds for failing to wear his sword to the exams (also
in the old regulations). :-)

The moral is that when invoking old rules, be prepared to have other
old ones invoked against you.

Feel free to chose some current laws that might still be on the books
in 1100 Imp. 

Another thought is that back when planets were first contacted and
brought into the Imperium, some of the (then) low TL worlds may have
had some *very* odd legal systems. Ones that may have become "frozen"
when they joined. 

This leads to things like players having a legal dispute on such a
world and being asked if they intend to fight themselves or hire a
"Gladiator at Law". 

Yep, a world where trial by combat is still the rule, but where it\'s
also been "modernized". 


"You have the right to trail by ordeal. If you decline ordeal, you are
 subject to trial by combat. If you are not fit to fight and cannot
 afford a champion, one will be appointed for you..."

If any of you use that bit in a "miranda Warning", I want to hear
about the player\'s reaction!

Heck, anybody got a copy of the *real* Miranda warning? Let\'s see what
we can do with it!

Check your history books for other methods of of rendering judgement. 

- -- 
