Really, the question is what level of coercion is sanctioned by law when
interrogating a suspect...

The issue is whether the information is admissable in court, and the Miranda
warning is given to CYA before questioning a suspect.  Giving the warning
helps  prove that the confession/admission wasn\'t coerced from an
individual.  I think the specific warnings vary in wording from one
department to another slighty.

I don\'t have a copy of an actual Miranda Warning handy right now, but here
is some information from "Criminal Procedure for the Criminal Justice
Professional":

- ----
- -Coercive police activity is necessary for an admission or confession to be
found involuntary.
- -Satisfaction of Miranda requirements is a relative consideration in
determining the voluntariness of an admission or confession, but it is not
conclusive.
- -Only voluntary admissions or confessions that are obtained in compliance
with Miranda requirements will be admissable in court.
- ----
This is under US law.

Generally, the Miranda warnings are required when interrogating a subject in
custody.  Admissions to private citizens and some other circumstances
(public safety,undercover agents, a voluntary statement made before the
officer has a chance to give the warning, ect) aren\'t restricted.

Basically, the warning is that you have the right to get a lawyer, you have
the right to keep your mouth shut for your own good until you get a lawyer,
and that anything you say can be used against you in court.  There are some
other parts too, but I can\'t remember them all.

I\'m not sure how the Imperium would apply this concept, I think their goals
are to keep an Intersteller economy running as smoothly as possible, keep
lines of communication open, and provide defense for the subject worlds.  I
have a DGP Traveller Digest with an article on Imperial Law that I can look
at and send more info later.  Offhand, I think that the Imperium would be a
little more liberal in what sorts of confessions (methods used to obtain
them that is) would be admissable in court.

As far as the individual worlds who knows???

I am not a lawyer, so if any of this is inaccurate, I apologize.


Craig
