    'body' => 'Once again, I feel it is time to repent for my off-topic posts. I all too
frequently use my voodoo folklorist powers for evil and point out that
certain stories posted to the list are urban legends. I will now use the
same voodoo folklorist powers for good and post some musugashimeku, or
spacelore.

I hope you enjoy the following trio of folktales! (Please keep in mind that
the bad grammar and rambling tone are both intentional.)

Collected in the Spinward Marches, 1090:

 "On Regina, there was this merchant, and he was really down on his luck.
His Beowulf had been reeped by the bank for non-payment and he had a couple
of crates of tripchins he needed to move off-world and he needed to do it
fast. So, he reads the newsfeed and up pops this for-sale ad for a puking
dog and the selling price is only 1 credit. He can\'t believe his eyes, and
he thinks it\'s got to be a typo. Still, he figures he\'s got nothing to lose,
and the address in the ad is within walking distance inside the starport. He
walks over there real quickly and ends up at the front door of what looks
like a small cartel. He almost turns \'round \'cause he can\'t think of any
reason this cartel would want to pawn off a puking dog for just one credit.
He rings the bell and this nice older woman answers. He says that he wants
to take a look at the ship, and she obliges him. The ship was in perfect
condition! As he\'s checking out the cargo hold the lady says to him, "You\'re
the only person who\'s come along since I put the ad in yesterday, I\'m
surprised." So he says to her, "Well, maybe nobody would believe the
misprint in the newsfeed." She just smiles at him at says, "Oh, it\'s no
misprint, I\'m really selling it for just a credit." The merchant can\'t
believe his own ears, he just about falls over. Finally, he asks what the
catch is, but she tells him there\'s no catch, so he asks why she\'s selling
it so cheap.

 "As it turns out, just before she put up the ad, she got an Xmail from her
husband, the guy who ran the cartel. It turns off he\'d run off with some
cute chippie and he wanted his wife to fire the crew of the puking dog, sell
it, and send him the money. So not only does this trader get this ship for
less than a soda, he also gets a line on a full jobless crew. This guy was a
friend of my wife\'s friend, and from what I understand his luck really
changed after that!"


Collected in Daibei, 1101:

 "Ugkfoung Akuedharrgh, that Vargr who plays Lucky in all of those Jetland
movies, was visiting Capital, and staying in this apartment his producer
owned in this real posh arco. Everyone knows that Ugk doesn\'t go anywhere
without the pet palgo that his friend Girur Duliirumar gave him. So, he\'s on
the elevator in this arco and these two old Impie ladies get on, they\'re
like 200 years old and both of them can probably trace their ancestry way
back to the Sirka and the Ramshackle Empire. So they see Ugkfoung, on the
elevator, and all Vargr look alike to them, and even if that wasn\'t the case
they wouldn\'t know who he was since they\'re like 200 years old and they\'re
on hoity-toity Capital and they\'ve probably never even *heard* of Tom
Jetland. So, they\'re real nervous and scared \'cause they\'re on the elevator
with this furry Vargr, and they\'ve never seen one before. Palgos can smell
fear, and they get all excited when they do, but these ladies don\'t even
realize that this palgo is moving toward them, they\'re so afraid of Ugk, but
he notices his palgo\'s getting all excited, and he orders it to sit. The
palgo sits, and so do the two old ladies. They thought this freaky Vargr was
ordering *them* to sit. Ha! I don\'t know what they were thinking!"

Speaking of palgos, here\'s another one, which was collected in the Spinward
Marches in 1098:

 "A belter I used to drink with told me this story, and it apparently
happened to his friend who was a steward or something with the crew that
this happened to. There was this free trader and they had a passenger who
had this palgo and she really wanted to keep this palgo in her stateroom
with her. The captain had his own set of regulations and rules, and he
didn\'t let her. I think it had something to do with insurance. The palgo was
to be kept in its cage in the cargo hold. Some cargo handler puts the palgo
in the hold, but there\'s a screw up with the cargo manifest and they vac the
hold for some reason.

 "So, a few weeks later, they get to the planet this passenger was going to,
and she keeps asking about her palgo. The captain realizes that they sucked
all the air out of the hold and the palgo can\'t possibly be alive, so he
tells her they\'ll deliver the critter to her place just as soon as they
unload it. She gets really mad, and she wants the palgo right away, but the
steward calms her down and she goes home. So, they\'re unloading the cargo,
and, sure enough, the palgo is dead. The captain sends his crew out to find
a palgo that looks the same and, as if by a miracle, they find one. They
cremate the dead palgo at the starport\'s fusion crematorium, and they put
the live palgo in the cage. The captain, feeling very badly, goes to deliver
it by hand.

 "So, he gets there and he hands the lady the cage, and her face goes red.
She gets really angry and she starts shrieking, " You thief, you liar! What
kind of business do you run!" The captain is really confused, the two palgos
looked *exactly* alike, he indignantly insists that it\'s her palgo. She gets
even madder and she screeches at him, "What do you take me for, a fool? I
know that even jumpspace cannot bring a dead palgo to life!"

 "It turns out that the palgo was her husband\'s, and the beast outlived him.
Her husband was very rich and left strict instructions in his will to bury
the critter at his feet when it finally died. She hated the little monster,
and she had to cut her vacation short to bring it all the way back home."
