> SW forces reaching Rhylanor. "So let the Zho\'s run to my
> home world. They\'ll be cut to pieces by our new ships and
> I\'ll break the sieges at Efate and Jewel."--Santanocheev

Porozlo is good.  I had considered Vilis, but it is a bit exposed to
attack.  I don\'t read Santanocheev as a traitor, BTW, just as an
incompetent and empire-builder.  He might go over the edge after his
downfall though, in an attempt to shaft his enemies.

We could assume that he was from Porozlo, and acquires estates on Vilis. 
This would give us an opportunity to bring him into the Tanoose/Garda-Vilis
question, where he could become a prominent hard-liner, demanding Imperial
intervention and the crushing of the Tanoose Freedom League.  This would be
a suitable way to use an ultra-conservative, "well-connected" Colonel Blimp
type - one of the possible ways to read this guy, particularly if we use
the reading of "Norris the liberal" that appears in MT Rebellion
sourcebook, and TNE Regency sourcebook, where Norris is the initiator of
the Representational Reforms.

> Finally, there is the inevitable Lucan/Santanocheev concept.
> I didn\'t want to do this; it seemed a little to tidy and cheesy.
> But I suppose one could connect the two. And for GT:Trav
> people, Lucan and Santanocheev\'s son might create some
> mischief. Not my IMTU; YMMV.

Yes, it\'s cheesy, and yes, it\'s pretty obvious, and thus "inevitable".  It
is actually pretty likely that socially well-connected young riff-raff
would flock together, and toadying would become an artform.  See the
"Flashman" books by George Macdonald Fraser for more details!

The other GT option would be people toadying Varian.  We don\'t know much
about him, so he could well be as pointless a sleazebag as Lucan.

En Garde is, of course, a useful guide to Imperial high society IMTU.

Alan Bradley
