    'topic' => ' Old laws/weird legal systems',
    'body' => 'Was Written:
>
>Check your history books for other methods of of rendering judgement.



Reputedly there was an old Chinese legal recourse, trial by kite.  The
accused was strapped to the frame of a huge kite.  If he survived the
launch, subsequent flight of a set duration, and landing he was innocent.
This is of course a variation of trial by ordeal.  Perhaps this is the
source of the expression "go fly a kite".

There is the method of judgement and also of picking a punishment where in a
random passage from some holy book is selected and interpreted for guidance.

Regarding Punishment

While not a judgmental method in the strict sense there is the method by
which, in ancient times, an accused may avoid execution by finding an unwed
woman to marry him.  Watch the movie with Jack Nickelson "Going South".

There is also the ancient principal of punishment by example where by one of
the group of the accused, selected by lot, is punished for the entire group.
The rest are allowed to live presumably having learned from the example.

There is the ancient form of punishment where by all ignore the existence of
the guilty and render no assistance to him or them.  On certain worlds with
closed environments this could mean no doors open, no food, no medical
assistance... nothing works for the guilty.

How about the ancient practice of "outlawing" where by the accused is
declared an "outlaw", forfeits all his goods and is given a running start,
in extreme cases naked, before hunting season is declared.  "Be out of town
by sun up."

How about the old S/F chestnut of being sentenced to the organ banks.  In
minor cases this would involve loss of a body part in more extreme cases
vivisection.

Just a few historical and fictional models of judgement and punishment.


Dan
