>> A/UX was Apple\'s UNIX implementation (or rather, impersonation), which was a
>> native UNIX which could also call the stuff in the Apple ROMs. It got dropped
>> in the early 90\'s in favour of AIX, which was in turn dropped shortly before
>> Jobs came back on board.
>
>No, no a thousand times no!! A/UX was Apple\'s Unix implementation, IIRC it
>was a BSD-ish variant. AIX is IBM\'s rather twisted sick and throughly
>weird implemntation of something that pretends to be unix. Only that
>FrankenUnix known as HP-UX comes close to AIX in weirdness.
>
Ummm, I\'m not sure where the thousand times no comes from. Apple stopped
selling A/UX and started selling their own RS/6000 implementations as servers.
There were a bunch of others doing similar - Hitachi, Motorola, Bull. Since the
hardware implementations (despite both the Mac and the RS using PowerPC) were
incompatible they had to run AIX as the OS. The Apple boxes were actually
pretty nice, but Apple had neglected to set up a channel capable of selling
them.

As for your opinion of AIX and for that matter HP/UX ... AIX is OK. I\'d prefer
it to HP/UX, sit it alongside Solaris and prefer Linux to all of them (though
for commercial use Linux still has a couple of things to sort out). I\'m amazed
that these statements about AIX still abound (probably from people who haven\'t
looked at it since 3.1). 

DomainOS was weird though, I\'ll grant you that.

