    'topic' => 'OT: Looking At 2000',
    'index' => 'ej521',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'Looking at 2000

You can listen to what you hear on TV and call it the New Millennium.
Or, you can count the years yourself and realize that the New Millennium
actually doesn\'t start until the year 2001--because Year 0 never
happened.

You can move through New Year\'s Eve enjoying the grandest party you\'ve
ever been to, or you can sit at home, alone, with Dick Clark, like it is
just another day, and have just as good a time.

You can move into tomorrow with goals of loosing weight, working out,
stopping smoking, discovering your soul mate, finding a better job,
writing a novel, or even making a movie.  Or, you can go to work on
Monday with nothing more on you mind than what you had going to work on
Friday.

The point is, there are as many ways to look at the New Year as there
are pairs of eyes around to look at it.  Find out what is most important
to you, and live that.

Be that.

I refer to a couple of cliches:  The way others perceive you is not as
important as the way you perceive yourself.  You just can\'t please
everyone, so please yourself.

As 2000 approaches me here in Houston, Texas USA, I extend my warmest,
best wishes and hopes for the New Year to those who own my heart, my
family and closest friends, and to everyone reading this message.

Your dreams will come true if you make them.  May your dreams come true
in 2000.

Kenneth D. Bearden
Walker Jane Productions



I leave you this year with a note, copied below, found handwritten on
Mother Teresa\'s wall.  Her words inspire and touch me.

============================

People are often unreasonable, illogical, and self-centered;
Forgive them anyway.

If you are kind, people may accuse you of selfish, ulterior motives;
Be kind anyway.

If you are successful, you will win some false friends and some true
enemies; Be successful anyway.

If you are honest and frank, people may cheat you;
Be honest and frank anyway.

What you spend years building, someone could destroy overnight;
Build anyway.

If you find serenity and happiness, they may be jealous;
Be happy anyway.

The good you do today, people will often forget tomorrow;
Do good anyway.

Give the world the best you have, and it may never be enough;
Give the world the best you\'ve got anyway.

You see, in the final analysis, it is between you and God;
It never was between you and them anyway.

    Mother Teresa, I
',
