From the Diary of Warrant Officer 1st Class Sven Lindstrom, Gram
Army.

Saurus, 171-1109

After dropping the infantry in the LZ, we laagered the gcarriers
on bit of high flat ground and waited.  I had seen a village a
few hundred meters below, and decided to investigate it.  The
villagers had all fled.  I wandered on dirt alleys between huts
made from thick leaves and wood.  In a rather elaborate hut, I
found a small, low bench on which incense and flowers had been
arranged.  The bench was beautiful, a work of art, artfully
fitting four kinds of wood together in a tongue-and-groove
construction, by a society that was not able to smelt iron.  I
stole it.  

I brought my trophy back to the laager and showed it to my
comrades.  "Look how strong it is," I said, standing on it.
"They made it without nails."

"Stupid Sauros haven\'t invented nails," said Sergeant Kjellsen.

- --with apologies to the author of Chickenhawk, the war memoir of
a helicopter pilot in Vietnam

