If it\'s the article I\'m thinking of, it\'s useless.  It tries to
turn the Imperium into the United States.

>Offhand, I think that the Imperium would be a little more 
>liberal in what sorts of confessions (methods used to
> obtain them that is) would be admissable in court.

In my Traveller Universe, the Imperial criminal justice system
is accusatorial, not adversarial.  Finding the truth, not
fairness of result, is the goal.  Imperial judges (whose noble
rank is at least Baron) have wide powers to investigate Imperial
crimes.  

The rights of the accused depend in part on the accused\'s rank. 
A noble has the following rights

- -to be released on bond, including the word of another noble;

- -to challenge the prosecution before trial to show that the
prosecution is motivated by evidence linking the noble to the
crime, i.e., that the prosecution is not politically motivated;
the noble may present evidence in support of the challenge;

- -to a trial before a tribunal of judges of equal or higher noble
rank, which is a quasi-adversarial proceeding; 

- -to examine the evidence against him or her before trial; 

- -to engage an attorney and investigators; 

- -to make any statement of explanation or exculpation; and

- -to accuse others.

A commoner has the following rights:

- -to engage an attorney and investigators; 

- -to make any statement of explanation or exculpation; and

- -to accuse others.

>As far as the individual worlds who knows???

Anything goes.  Under the Imperial agreement with each world,
every world may enforce its own laws against anyone within its
territory except for the starport, Imperial facilities, and
officials from the Imperium with diplomatic credentials. 
Officials from other worlds, whether Imperial or not, are
normally given diplomatic immunity as well.  

- --Glenn
