>     I think Arthur may have a point here, what does the TL mean? Is it the
> TL of the facility or the TL of the society/culture on the station? It is
> concievable that the people on the station live an austere lifestyle in a
> very old, very automated enviroment. We may think that our mania for planned
> obsolescence which is a facet of our society holds true for Traveller, but
> maybe not. Maybe the culture that constructs these habitats builds for
> keeps, the station itself may be ancient. Just a few rambling thoughts while
> I endure this hangover (shudder)

Another possible explanation is that the world\'s infrastructure doesn\'t
support production of goods above the listed TL, nor are items above the
listed TL routinely imported _for consumer use_.  However, if, for
instance, the belt is a mining world, it may prove worthwhile (depending
on the substances mined) to import high-tech life support machinery. 
This would not necessarily reflect in the world\'s listed TL, since folks
going to that system can\'t expect to buy items of the higher TL, nor can
the get repairs on any of their high-tech equipment.

